======== SAMPLE 1 ========
imming
with the sun, her mouth a hot, cracked-over grin.

The smell of her hair: roses and powdered sugar and bourbon, sugar and rum and honey, sugar and spice.

The softness and brightness of her body: the natural sweetness of love, a security and forgiveness.

The trip to Benares: a walk on the banks of the Yamuna, a sea-jump, a marriage-salvation.  She is cool and green in Saravan.

Day after day, she gets more and more naked every decade.  When she was a small girl, she dreamed of getting off the mattress 
and entering the sea. Now she dreams of getting off the mattress and entering the sea.

It happens that her mother is in the bathroom 
shaving with water her mother is sitting on the toilet (she's very handy with soap) when she sees Millet 
rising from the bath. She doesn't stop to think what's happening to Millet.  She 
shaves Millet's legs, moans in Vittoria, gets angry.  The smell of Millet in front of her.

She throws Millet out of the window.  He gets sick and dreams of getting off the mattress.  He gets very sad and violent.  Then he tells his wife Bridget. 

Five days later, Millet wakes up in a hotel in Saravan.  He feels that the best thing to do is to jump in the Amtrack 
and watch the tracks burning in the nearby fields.  At the present moment he sees a tranquility unlike any other.

Milton and Jones own the place and keep the gold and drugs and pleasures -- they keep the black swans and keep the flies away.

and they know their own names. 

on a dark and sore day, 
when joy and pride are rare,
    to fight for them is set on,   
and all their enemies are near,   
and none can tell what should be done. 

    but let them be. 
they must not stay long. 
    some of their friends are sick,   
and many are young. 
    they think of home, 
and of the war that befell them. 

    where they were a country,    
in most ancient times said 
    their main streets were rocky,   
and they made their boast,   
that if they lost only by stroke,   
the mountain to the eastward   
would befall them. 



and out of the west   
a new nation arose,   
and out of the east   
a star shone, and from the west   
rose like flame, in a dream. 

that ancient country they were,   
the same as now old   
from their side to ours, yet 
    not one could move a foot   
and the people they were,   
as we now see them, stood. 



in some years 
a man shall fall by the wayside   
and no one may say for the sake   
of such a death of a man 
as it fell to the ground.   

but this is no accident 
that such a man fell,   
and thus we have no cause to grieve.   

in other years 
one cannot tell the wars 
by their early quietness. 

even then who would be there? 
who would feel old and sad? 

and would they have a friend to say good-bye   
when such a one passed away?   

for one will not go alone, 
and nothing will guide one's footsteps 

in so sad a world, where shoes must be worn   
to the end of the world,   
and the soul, though always still, 

must creep from the house to the church, 
and every little thing must move, 

but there was a man with whom I always met   
and what do you know about, or how he died?   

he was about the fifth of the ninth century,   
and lived in a corner of a very small building,   
under an above-mentioned and very windy roof. 

he was of the king's chamber, and wore the crown   
long-vested in his left eye, where the light was plain   
in a sky that was darker than a full year, 

and now you will recollect the quaint way   
we were saved from many dreams at the house of the late king,   
and the quiet and soft sounds from the church 

that kept us at home, and were in our music at night,   
when the lady sang, and the peasants sang, and the little boys   
roared triumphantly to the music before them. 

and when the king died, and we, who had not been born,   
sat by the little window of the church, we thought   
we saw the dead king, and for a time we did not cry, 

for we did not understand what was going to happen   
to us, for we did not know how we were going to die. 

but we were glad when the tomb, when the coffins   
filled with the gray ashes of the past, opened, and we know   
there were many things that the king was good for,   

and then a human figure walked in 
the frost was shining upon the grass   
like a man without a face, and he sat down,   
and he saw two angels--one angel   
in silver mask and one in gold--

and he said, that they were good to him, which he said   
they were.
and they made him happy, and took his hands   
and kissed them, and thanked him for them. 

and one angel said, to one who did not know,

 of what we call 
the other kind


i can give you one piece of the puzzle, and then maybe 
you can go and do something with it. to begin with, yes, 
but there are seven stones on the top that must be 
scattered about the spots. you must find them, find 
what is on each stone 
and on what was on the other piece. i will teach you the words 
that will be helpful.


                                                                               i found, 
to be a small, but vibrant, 
                                                                                                              in a patch 
of light.


my friends,
see the light coming through the night
of the friends within the light
of the life within the light of
the friends.

they are not dreaming of
only the dead, the blue night of
the friends,
but of the friends, and of the life within,
the light of the blue night,
                                                                       and the life
of those that are now napping, or playing 
games. oh, what a fine time to be alive 
when the great lights of the city
that make us forget the dead
come again to light our living--
                                                                                                        i love you,
blizzard to me as it were,
but the earth, the earth,
came through the sea
as the blue sea, the sea of blue,
                                                                               and the light,
the blue, of friendship
come to light as the sea
                                                                                                                with deep
black eyes
as they are always,
as they are always,
in their blue-white clouds
of clouds.


the black sledge's black as a dream,

as the lightnings all through the sea,
like a man into the dark, all in a dream,

as the sea of my mind went out toward that end
in the day, at its heart, in the dark.

what does the black-and-white of a dream have to do 
with a man looking to his death in the dark?

how does it work? it is like seeing another's eyes,
as a man who looks at his own mind goes to another's.

a dream is what is beyond your dream,
the white clouds above the distant future,

with the night being all that's behind the daytime and the morning after the sun. 

on the contrary, when people come against the nativity with all its pomp and circumstance, 
they celebrate it with an air of one who's deaf, dumb, or insane.

 earthquake but not, i repeat,   

i don't think she knew that, though I could imagine   

some young men, her size, maybe, her blue taupe skin,   

but that's just me. I'm also Lisa of Etruria 

who might have been half her age at once 

having taken an apprentice in the Appian Way, 

which might have been Italian, but was born in Greece, in Mycenae, 

where Mycenae is so badly lit that you can hear   

the crackle of your barbed wire against bent   

plaster or the squeak of cranes which are lifting hay 

at the touch of the wind. There must have been   

millions, and millions upon millions, of little men   

holding their breath   

as though there were a connection, and each had   

one, too, and they all worked for a living, not   

as though, put this way,   

there were three kinds of men, the master,   

the carpenter, and the planter. 

And so I imagine them, sitting at the table 

again, each one   

taking out his little tin lamp 

whose stroke of pink was   

almost exactly one of a green leaf. 

Each one   

held his tool   

in his left hand. 

And there was women,   

holding their milk white bottles   

back   

with a curtsey smile, each 

fingering one of her hands. 

And there were children,   

with their faces red 

by not getting enough sleep,   

fed-up looking   

and hungry   

from having no milk   

or butter   

from the company of whom   

            but actually from the company of Joanne   

they must have known   

Joanne and her friends   

everybody knew and liked her, 

even lost in the forest 

here she was commanding, commanding   

the little l-shaped group-- 

a group of children who 

got along so well,   

bunny, cardigan, black-suited,   

bright smile, that faces it all. 

She is calm and good-looking,   

unlike any young woman here. 


The Party
There now it is,
your clavicle and balls,   
your rump, your warm-water 
tank and all and its carapace. 

It will keep you warm,
being made of collagen, 
no harm, no regret. 

To call it a party was   
invented by the sun
when it was just a little leaf,   
you've got to smash it, you've got to   
blow it away.

There once was a lake of it,
called herself the Calf,
and the whole world went wobbly, 
wondering what she'd become. 

Calf--she'd never been one--
was the name she took
when she slipped through
the kitchen tent and slipped behind the couch, 
into nothing's lap.

Everything lived on,
salt-water and snow,
the street lamps stood on,
and church spires stood on,
standing in nothing's shadow. 

Now the spire has split,
and the candle ends its life 
in the wind, in the wind
mill, in the wind, in the wind. 

And the sea dead,
the sea dead, the sea dead.
There are no angels in the sky. 

But in the sky there is a lamp, 
in the sky there is a John
doing his three jobs: 

First, he checks the weather:
then he sorts through the leaves
to see if it gets dark, 
if the rain comes and go.

John lights the living things:
he goes down the steps of the Cooper Union
and up the steps that lead to his own balcony
and takes a couple of cans of soup.

John knows the colors:
take Hazelnut shells, he says,
or find where

======== SAMPLE 1 ========
 have been on
these tracks for days, waiting
for you to come, waiting
to hear you say this would work.

When you finally did come by that winter, you held a stack of old newspapers. They were marked by name after a letter, and the sender wished you could read them. It was a cherry tree. It had been there all the same.

When the mail had arrived, and you had removed the tags, you still wished to come. You had, and you were a little surprised to see how easily you had been tricked. The mail had come to your home, and it was only a matter of walking two or three inches. You could have brushed it off, as it were, and gone on with your life. And you did go on with your life, happily.

But then, one day, you realized that you were not at home. And you called the police. And then you thought, This seems like a story that could have been called "nothing short of being cataclysmic."”������������������������

Each and every day, the media covers the most trivial of topics, like the childless bathroom 
blue-eyed Barbie, the government telling us how our healthcare costs are 
rising, all with the blithe profits of multinationals.

It is all a gigantic scam, what can be bought or sold. 
Follow me down to the heart of our factory, where often thousands of tiny drones do 
and carry our medicine to patients. Here, too, the police and the medics and the inspectors and the inspectors and the chemists and the veterinarians and the mechanics and the accountants and the accountants are mixing doll-like powders with human hair and needlessly bright-eyed 
dogs spraying the working girls with poison so that the hospital’s lights be 
on throughout the afternoon so that the drones can keep up.

I confess I did not know, how the media supposed, that a cry could be a cry of fear. 
Cry me a little, and you’ll notice how the snakes keep working. 
The more they spit, the more those skulls. 
The more they suck, the more adrenaline builds up in them, 
and they begin to snort and aggressively stab each other again.

DEAD CITY

 This dead city longs to be 
This dead city longs to be free 
Seven screaming horses 
Melt down in the sun 
Building scenes in the s, 
These scenes crumbling slowly 
Like gelatin capsules breaking, 
Slowly melting down into capes 
That can’t breathe anymore. 
How long will it be until this 
Animals park in the sun? 
There is the word 
The word can’t swim anymore 
The cities of the flesh

 syndrome

anomaly – physical condition or event distinct from and distinct from a typical clinical phenomenon; for example, the appearance of cold fusion proteins or a persistent pattern of magnetic resonance imaging selective for the nucleus forebrain cortex

anterior cerebral artery a branch of the internal carotid artery; supplies blood to the medial aspect of the cerebral cortex (leg area dominant, including the superior collicospinal tract) and to the medial aspect of the cerebral peduncle (including the superior longitudinal fasciculus and internal capsule)

anterior commissure one of the four major groups of fibrous tissue lying between the arachnoid and midbrain that receives blood from the main circulation and enters the diencephalon via the foramen of the midbrain

anterior communicating artery branch of the internal carotid artery that joins together the paired anterior cerebral artery and the paratonic plate

anterior cranial fossa portion of the internal base of the skull housing the intermedial pontineles; supplies blood to the medial temporal lobe, brainstem, and cerebellum

Anton's syndrome form of neurofibrillary degeneration characterized by obsessions, compulsive movements, barrel-like posturing, and ataxia/diadojia (acute and progressive ataxia and progressive ataxia/diabetes mellitus)

aphasia syndrome of excessive daytime sleepiness, which can result from disorders of the circulatory system, respiratory system, and blood vessels (e.g., idiopathic facial tonic regional atrophy of the facial nerve and too much sodium in the blood)

aphlogon free-ranging phagocytoma histologically benign blood vessel disease associated with underactive immune response

aphoneuropathy nerve disease associated with underactivity in phagocytic processes; nerves are usually classically ganglionic (i.e., class of nerves that innervate all cranial nerves in the body) but occasionally also mechanistically separate (using nerves outside the spinal cord)

amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (Lou Gehrig's disease or ALS) inexorably progressive and lethal neurodegenerative disease associated with deterioration in motor function that occurs as the disease progresses and progressively worsens over time, eventually rendering it untreatable

amyotrophic loss of nerve supply generally restricted to the loss of motor neurons through caloric or metabolic means, including hypoxic insults

malignancy uncontrolled invasion and expansion of a neighboring immune cell population, usually by monocyte/macrophage invading

massacre usually nuclear, but also refer to the generalized reaction to violence

medial leukoencephalopathy see posterior fossa

medication overuse drug withdrawal syndrome associated with light-ankle congestion associated with reflex eye movements maximally mediated via the thalamus and subthalamic nuclei

medication overuse disorder of excessive and indiscriminate use of any commercial pharmaceutical medication

medz-vous syndrome of Tourette syndrome characterized by visual hallucinations, hirn'-ing, and ataxia/hyperacusia in response to ophthalmologic stimuli

massage bathing seizure epilepsy type characterized by sudden, severe, displacement of the entire cranial block and its furniture, muscles, tendons, ligaments, tendons, and sinuses through the entire limbia, emaciated muscle, brain, peripheral nerves, and grafts on to the lesioned head

mecropsychoic disorder of the brain occurring in infancy and occurring in childhood and affecting the nervous system and behavior at a rapid rate

meningeal carcinomatosis white fluke mass, usually in the cervical region, spinal cord, or pons, growing slowly with age

meningitis inflammation of nerve tissue

meningocele failure of bone fusion in the posterior midline of the vertebral column resulting in a bony cleft through which the meninges and varying tracts later resolve; a lesion of the meninges, typically the posterior ones, can result in severe sensory nerve deficits in the affected body

meningoryluscular junction (myelin sheath) portion of the axon that is guated, and is attached to the plexus myotonia and the humerus magnus by glial cells. Structurally, it is composed of the same nerve fibers as the motor neurons but is modulated by the cuticle sacs and perineurium by various preganglionic and autonomic modulatory fibres.

meningyphoidosis see tuberculous malformation

meningoryphonus see tuberculous malformation

 to the sky.


and when i stood to-day's self with eyes of gold

                                                                                                                                                         in the little town of stowe,
 
             and there i found him bound and tied
  he spent the daylight in the hayblanket,
                                on a spit of wood,
                                                     with a stone.
 
                                                               there he ran
                                                      in the snow,
                                                        and it was black.
 
                    he was frozen to the marrow--
                                                                   and he was cold.
 
                                                        he could scarcely endure--
                                                                in the black he was
                                                                 less than a skater on a river--
 
                                          but he was not a skater.
                                   his brother, in the mines,
                                                      knew exactly why
                                                he would work

 in a black man's dream, 
i don't want you to be afraid of death
                          yet 
it is all i can do to keep my life 
from fading into the black man's 
                                                  life 
now i see you standing in the light 
                 outside your own garden
   and i think it is enough 
to trust in the hearts and your own sense 
                  of love
              to keep faith
not in the hearts and the feeling
               of love
              but in the mutual
supplication of all the dead

and close your eyes. it is enough
to see the light
                   in your own life
   there is the darkness, and the dark.
              the light
              will stay there
              till winter comes
and the spring leaves fill it up.


the old man rose from his shoes at six a.m.   
the big bird flew past both his shoes   
the old man carried his feet as if asleep   
and looked around for the source of the light 

he did not see the woman standing above him   
cleaning up, or the man sitting on the porch   
sitting alone, or those two children 
games played in the backroom of the hut 

at the fire, the youngest crying because nothing 
had happened that morning 
the children were wordless, the mother   
watching them with their mother 

and now darkness 
fell across the snow-hut, people 
running for the boats, the huts 
gaining speed, some hopping mad in 
the high wind and this man who 
saw the white lady in a passing car, maybe   
a stray hint of her melancholy, 

and that hattie, hannah ran   
as a buffalo in the frozen wood 
that buffalo, seen from the road, might   
take shelter under 
and cling to the top of a tree instead 
of freezing.


he ran to the road 
and up the dead-end road 
along the mountain road 

the car was tossed into a cloud   
and cast out 
          it took years 
before they could tire 

of their mane and eyesight,   
they began throwing 
the body around like a bean 

with a full face and tail   
they twisted the body 
          like a new twig

at every angle 
the body got lighter   
          all the eyes 

they took one last look   
          the dead man's 
opened mouth as flat 
          as a table cloth


a tale of two cities

miles from the shore on a still night
there was a city
on the lake, hidden by fog,
its spluttered, wooden crests
in the mounds
built at the base of a hill
or chitchat in early darkness
the lights of it
in the city
in the fog, a great city
in the moonlight.

it had no bridges
its streets were narrows
filled with men
like iron filings through
a town of skulls without
a few rusty guns
rooted in the sternbone

and all the women
shouting from the corners
of their eyes
are fragments of conversations
the light, which had
attached itself to the pines,
touched down and gone out,
and the fog attached to it, and that
place was death.

how people hid
how bridges were tied
to corpses' legs
and

======== SAMPLE 1 ========
 want like to see
     
ourselves in their last agony 
     
of childhood woe. they lie 
tucked in the dark, as if knowing 
     
the sound of that hour
     
to weep a tear.

they are on the cold slab 
      
and the sun is upon them, 
     
like mournful gods.


in the heat of the midday the furor   
of exultation, of pleasure, begins anew. 
our heart-eyes, soft white fleas 
or notions about union 

in the light's trivial reverberations   
the grandire salutes, salutes, salutes. 
as if they were the future's new sins. 

but it is in the dark of history   
that these children are being made. 
in the midsummer of our joy, 
in the fall of our laughter, in the winter 
of pain and ice, these are the ghosts that we have made. 

we who are the roots of the flood 
hold in our hands things that would bring us joy,   
taken into the house of the season,   
cooked and carried and brought to term. 

as our first years of rubeor 
are passed, all our serene and active powers, 
so we run our businesses in the quiet of the dying day,   
though the lights come up in the darkness. 

and we whose hearts are breaking 
bathe in the deep pools of mortality, 
we who are the smoke, the color and the light   

turn after another year, in the quiet, 
our long, white faces, formal as cats, are crying.


he keeps his morning coffee in a brown bowl at the table 
above the bed. he sits, as usual, with the book 
to side his eyes. this makes the mornings difficult, i guess 
the world has changed and the night's become 
a novel, i think, but he's not ready to accept 
that his meager, single dramenge of memoranda 
has become a novel of sadness. at any moment, in the dark 

of the woods, a bird could be heard twitching out. 
he keeps his morning coffee in a brown bowl 
and because the jet stream is always cold, naturally,   
i cover it. there's a book of dreams where birds 

fly around the forest on their warm 
chariot. at any moment the birds would be flying 
away, and it would be very small. now, at this moment, in the wild blue   

woods, at the edge of the page, there are no trees. 
as soon as anyone has noticed, there's a new bird 
apparently searching the whole world. it wants only 
to go out and look. that's all there is to it.


this season, the white sparrows have fled, birds 
have been chased from their nests and flocks, 
the brilliant goslings gone missing. 

and yet, somehow, winter holds on. 
first, the throat feathers are bright with frost, 
then gradually the moultings will stop, 

and the young will be back to feed and mate. 
if the red-tailed blackbirds keep 
their white tail feathers wet, the world won't long 

for these songs, these sweet songs.


let me tell you why waking is so hard 
to the common folk. first, you need 
to find a quiet place to call one's sleep 
you need to say your goodnights, consider 
how many people you know have died 
to make way for you in a hurry, 
and then you needn't hurry anymore. 
if you get there early enough, you'll likely see 
sky looming over your field of almond green 
and if the night isn't as ominous 
as you fear it will be, you'll know 
that even the drawers of the late afternoon are empty.


it was a small farm in a meadow 
near carroll, north carroll, 
marchin farm, north meadow farm. 
charlotte and me first fell in love. 
we lived on a meadow and also 
on a farm another meadow. 
we each owned a farm. 

we were poor farmers, munching on cherries, 
pudding, sugar, cornflakes.

======== SAMPLE 1 ========
                                                                 
 
in the dead of night
the voices come up
                  how many people
      are silent with pain
                       how many
      are silent with fear
                               how many
                                                        wantonly
                        before the angels,
                                                          and the soul
                                                           goes out and comes home.
                         in the dead of night
                                                          let others whisper
                                that he
                                                                 is dead,
                                          let the soul be formed
                                                            to endure.
 
                    this is the year


                you shall learn
                your mother tongue
                                                                     and use it
                         once in the mine.
 



i
 

to teach the words to you was labour
      and like a soft drink
      of yours a drop of spring
      from your eye a little gush,
      a tear and the whole in a jar.
  
                                 the first morning
                                was always dawn,

======== SAMPLE 1 ========
 told 

the living that can hear or sight may walk

he saw with what motion he made the whole world

go round his sight.

                                                  to him

the power that sight hath, and all that hears, 

rebelys.

                                                    he hears

with what power the eye has the world may see

               the globe round about its sphere,

and on the world's globe the power of sight

may not stop or block the power of the soul.


                                                       can it do

with all this power, whether such be it, 

or such was the will of thy father,

                i see, which was the will.

thou in no way doubting couldst thou behold

that miracle on earth, which alone could fail,

thou art filled with such a consciousness.

                 and such was thy will,

for in thee we see but glimpses as they were

when first the world in view did us see.


                                               it is not

some fancy work, but it is of the world,

that this form, this word has borne,

and is but sign in a dry sign

that hath neither sense, no motion,

nor form to another.


                              we are here

i wept and trembled, and cried, here wept, oh wept 

all around, but the mountain's white

ceilings hung down like smoke in the gloom, 

and the tears that seemed to spill all night down, 

fell incessantly at midnight, and all night long.


                                             it is not thus

but there has been with the word spoken

and that word is life of nature, man's own word 

and man in man's own name for we are all we have.


                           the snow is white and the sea is warm,

and near the shore that is not visible

is a mountain-top, its hair is grey,

its eyes are dark with the weather so dark,

that you might see the reflection we might make 

by love alone, and love alone

there's no other life but around this word.


                                           all around

the mountains are beautiful, the sea far and wide

with the moon the moon moves in the west,

                                             there's another thing

the great heaven envoys to us, and bids

                                         thy lover come.

and man, to the spring which opens

his mouth to the world upon the hill's hill

is grown fat and sad, his work is done,

The chest of a recluse is like a gigantic bathtub,
you can see all kinds of squishy baby bits oozing out,
and in the bathtub the squishy squirming kittens play.
Baby teeth chatter in the dental bore,
baby fingers plant their fingertips in the flood of dental plaster,
and a wooden chair rests on its mass of pillows.
A dead man's crown of gold is gathering dust,
and the wind charges down from the skies of the damned.
Now dressed in the caliginous regalia of the damned,
they apparate in the imperial manners of the clergy,
and gracefully move through the streets of this hellish city.

But I look at these people from afar,
I look at their faces, and I think,
to tell you the truth, they are nothing anymore,
informally, legally blind,
they are in the streets,
they are dancing and jiving and scratching their heads together,
they are carrying bundles of rope and sheets,
they are shrieking, they are rolling their trunks around in the air,

and I look at their faces,

they are nothing anymore,

 law.

But we all saw that laugh with a bitter look
Which haunted me like the thought of a stain upon the soul.

In vain they try to debase me with drugs--as if
I were nothing but the drug of the moment.

God should have kept me in life's meanings,
And turned my back on the world,
Instead of spurning corpses over with their flies.

But, with the specter of a prison door,
I turn my back on you all,
And solemnly say

"I reject your cruel impositions."
"Indeed I deplore your attitude.""

You've burned my youth, generation's whiteness."
"Did I not raise my voice to you as your god?"
"Does he not see that I'm running out of breath?"

"Careful observers may judge this bird from another."
"Generation's whiteness was its domain."
"Its domain was judgement."


II

Blasphemy—the crime of blasphemous murder of one of its own
names, or casting out of the skin, eroding or shattering
the flesh through a cut or cut on the outside, or by suffocation
so that the spirit carcass becomes blotched or floats abroad
abandoned or forgotten or dead—is part of the body's stock,
and, exposed, dies or is wasted away.
It is mortality without irony, and without contentment.

How can I then, my fallen brother,
describe in detail the next phases of your meteory descent
and what these have done to you, and have already done to me?

Part I: nocturnal and special fires
I wake to this most urgent sound, misted and flickering like tar
above my flickering lamp.

The closest I come to your ear is the nape of the neck,
and there's both relief and a terror to this hush.

Your tongue is most valuable now; and still more so
with the right one in your pocket.

Everything stops, wavering in its pearls and unanswered.

How can I describe its worth in words, or how it breathes action?

Here, a dollar amount and an air of money could be
unbinding.

How can we describe our love until we're sure of it?

A strange shape, glassy, opens in my chest,
I feel its shape and size and strength.

Our bodies are small and frail. Yours is not the same
as mine.

Kneeling to pray, half-naked and half-jockstrapped,
we put on our best.
Does it feel comfortable?

This is a silly song to you.
We don't need your quaver in our ears.

We don't need anyone—

Please refrain these lines from hatrackal rhetoric,
and I beg you to set your houses abonne.
 
 
Poetics
 
what’s lost is loss; the poem doesn’t lose itself.
 
/ Joseph Ceravolo
 
 
what lost are the roots of loss — lost through age, lost by fate,
 
lost by nobody, through age and death alone.
 
/ Max Brooks
 
 
these crooked leaves speak of colors “dark” and “white.”
 
These leaves speak of the childhood of color.
 
A hairbrush will go out in the next room, and the child
will be black.    These lines are my son’s eyes.
 
 across the street from the slanted windows of a boarded up
schoolhouse is a church.   When the train crosses the bridge of saint enric
 
Monsieve Campos Jr. is the small white ray of light in the morning,
 
and now it’s back to the translation, the full realization,
the ­­muscle in the brain, the ­­glia in the blood.
 
Language becomes erratically ambiguous, the interpretation,
 
                              double blind.
 
It’s absolutely insane for a photo to be displayed in a book,
                              or in a book - obviously
 
photos are the garbage of the moment, they 
                              lie about tragedy
 
borrowed from a well of water,
                                              or from the breastbone
 
of a porcelain pitcher.
                                              Or maybe it was stolen from
                                              the child’s hair?
 
Wow, this moment in a museum is really pretty,
I’d like a car to get here, eh? The woman
 
elsewhere

======== SAMPLE 1 ========
, 
and now in silence the world would be done. 
how they sat as one, and now, as one moved, 
what peace or sight or love or joy or all might have, 
but one, i thought, their last sight. and now, now 
only theirs the eye recalls to the past. 

and the eye was rapt, as we had been taught to be,   
and the mirth that so amused, in spite of all   
a man may employ, the moments between they   
is proper pain. why, as if man were not,   
shall they not be, too, alike to end   
their mortal lives with pain? the thought shocks us 
the world ends, our lives end. i was not one 

but each, the world and the world's last   
pried heart, i thought, as it ought, were alike,   
it may be these latter days are to a child 
not the child, that has not come of days yet   
to bring us to that grave, in the face   
of others as they were then, the quiet   
and peaceful lips, sewn with many a lace. 

i knew not each day would come, but remembered,   
as he to one who never came alive,   
and as the old vowour of those who were born,   
tho' and while our heart in bower moor lands slept,   
he made his way the path of the empty.   
and he has not made the shawl of the sky,   
yet we are quiet at the fall, for the bird   
notes, on our faces, our hearts' blood beat.   

how vainly then we look to heaven, that dead   
and while it stands at us still, and wonders rest,   
we turn the head, until our prayer rings, and lifts   
our eyes above ourselves, and sees us not.   
only our blood, like the dead, lives in us,   
as the world's own life-blood dies. only 

the world's cold bones shall be bright with blood when   
we rise, though they lie hidden there, though they sleep 
under our feet for ever. only a little more 
is left for us, the shapely and brave soul   
that should guide in the days to come this other way 

but no more. we tremble at the thought of one,   
or of all things, but at once, who knows,   
that it is the world's unerring duty   
to make us immortal in its inexorable fate.   
but still, at least we dream, and dream a little better,   
for we dream, though the world seems to fail, 

and with sleep the soul surrenders to it and sinks   
in its irredeemably blind hell.


 
the child is being born, and the green apple on the vine   
smeared with the foulest taste of hogblood. the land is warm as oil,   
and a few leeks wind about the shade. on the mead-barrel fens   
fishes their rows. in the wharves the fishmonger has his clammersack   
and the sailors wear white sails. at anchor there are brigand ships   
thrown overboard, but the men are unhatched. they have not hatched,   
nor garlanded on the newborn infant of the sea. the crew are young   
and beautiful, as pilots who dream, and whose very joy   
is the buoyant sun. the land is firm, and so, in the fiddle-fishing   
ploth, the mariners build their keel. deep in the shallows a ring   
of lee-poiter crawls, and in it the longshore devils,   
devils and young men with their blatey hookers ride,   
and the ship's head is brown with bredters. 
   the fishmonger has his clammersack, and the ship's head   
is boding in the young men with their blatey hookers.   
a horse was galloping, like a horse of ill omen,   
when the sudden peeling lemon peeled the keel.   
behind, the heavy-

the first and last hope of history, and so   
you have to die a little dying. 

you have to dream a little false dream, and so   
you have to dream a little true dream. 

the first and last hope of history   
is to dream a little false dream, 

so don't you jest when i ask what it takes   
for men like me to dream what we dream-- 

that we're growing fat in between, 
and not at the first but later glance, 

as i dream i dream, or dreaming i dream--   
but in meaning i dream as i see 

each day is a full rich day, with enough   
of me and of each day, that it's fun 

to think of the little fatuousness and truth   
we enjoy as fun. and we're careful 

as where our fatuousness will be ness   
while we're here among all 

to enjoy the day in peace, as 
the day is near? think again. we're here 

to make love. it's not like we're 
afar into love, not like a man into a woman 

for profit. not like we're the stars 
or the stars are the nights. not like we're a man 

in love with a woman, at least one of us,   
and one of love. so don't 
gasp at me when i say i dream, don't 

ask me, can i see you now? don't stare.   
that's not true either. look around you, 

and if you want a better look at the day,   
i won't say there's no way, 

i'll say the dream is over here as now.   
i'm taking the night i'm sorry for. in two days 

i swear i will leave without asking why.   
i'll get out and get a drink and walk 

all the night, myself still reeling from the dream   
i had last night and lying down 

to see if the dream was for me.


at the old house along the creek under the trees, 
cattle slept through the night, even the cats in the dark. 

the river dropped a quarter-mile to the snows of algonquin,   
half that longs to change its course and be naked again. 

with old mattresses and new pajamas, we were going out 
to cheer ourselves from bed, and when we were through,   
the longed-for wind was blowing. that was how we went, 

naked for three days in the icebox, our skins smelling of apricot. 
indigo nightshade, a true south outfit, untired yet proud, 

giving us all the warmth we'd ever wanted in a hut.   
the campfire was getting dark, and the little girls were playing 

those awful wooden boards, far more than we'd know   
old bodies we'd seen bones turned to ash, and i said, 

i hope no one thinks i'm saying that i felt sorry for them,   
which i did--every thing i could for that child . . . and as for avenge, 

that was a sin. i did feel sorry for mum, who's dead, although she didn't know   
about these children. i blamed her--or her living wife, who was 

her mother--something more. almost as if i were   
to blame, i suppose, for everything. my young son 

was safe under the care of his wise father, who taught him and me so,   
i never did see him again. i made a promise not to tell. 

and now that they are gone, i feel so bad for them,   
so bad for the girl who lives in her own house 

and doesn't want to go out for walks and snacks   
in her at night, to go to someone's house and listen 

to the horrible rustling in the firerugs, to think   
she could be forgiven for what she did to deserve it.


my mother was right about me. i never knew 
enough to know what was in her past that made her angry,   
so much anger, so much self-hatred, so much self-hatred that   
i began to walk, not walking,

======== SAMPLE 1 ========
 heat, 
a faint heat in which what else was had 
could make a manainance, or, else, 
how soon may it be, with dewy eyes, 
i shall see the day when i have death.


if i were a dead horse, or a horse in heat, 
      and looking into a hot sun to heat my mind, 
my heart did its usual thing, but my mouth to bite 
      or bite another's neck when heat ran in the head. 
my mouth was always ready to heat my head. 
what was the use of my existing mouth, 
i thought, if i were already made one. 
this was nothing but an inconvenience, nothing 
      but a lip or a gape were it to my beauty. 
when a body's got up a head, it gives kind birth 
      to a new body anew in hot flame. 
i was a man with the strength of trees 
      in a frozen meadow, i was oh, i was. 
when he went down as his passions ran high, 
      in a hot sun to heat his mind, 
i was not to my age made tired by frost, 
      or famishing. i had bread and thought, 
i had words to say to words. i had sex and said no, not even 
      i wanted the boy, just the man. 
i had a power in my mouth, and no age. when i gave birth 
      to another, gave birth to my son, i was a man.


the moon and stars were dying out, 
the grass shook and opened its doors. 
all the birds sang and turned the earth's mouth. 
the night was dark with the dying stars. 
it is the same with our lives," said the woman in her sleep. 
i don't know what will happen to me then," she said.


it's raining in the village. 
it has been raining for three weeks now. 
late july through small windows 
on the big wooden bridge that rides up 
over the small river. 
heavy is the river, it is overtaking us. 
it would be easy to get away. 
but we live here with our broken limbs 
and frames where something strange might be. 
black in the dark cracks of the ground, the banks gray, 
the shadows ominous. is this the son 
of the one whom god 
created and then left behind? are we 
the fragments? do we dance from the shadow out, 
sharing the half-life? is my lover mad, 
and me the made one whole? was it love? 
she was young, and he was a fool, 
and we would not have had him for company. 
those were the days i loved, and i 
lost much. but the river carries on 
with its young swifts, 
fifty-five, still there. 
they call it godly, though it is slow to do. 
we would be open then, if god were not.


the great stone of kush 
made men happy, 
made sorrow great 
the changing seasons bring 
green buds and white blossoms fall 
showing the signs of summer they 
turn, they turn and smile, 
for joy in its turning. 
the stone that is clean 
makes food at will 
it is a seat of sitting well 
it is a sun with but one wheel. 
whenever rain is on the earth, 
food is piled high in the house. 
whenever wind is on the earth, 
food is lowered down for eating. 
ice is thrown into the fire, 
without asking why. 
ice that is peeled and served, 
ice that is broken and made love 
with a smile that is broken yet bright. 
ice cracks that are broken yet more bright. 
hard by a rock there is a place to sleep 
ice that is broken but a shelter from snow. 
in the snow a fish dips and moves 
it is white snow, snow so white fast 
no snow man can stand in it, 
no snow can stand in in the snow. 
ice is thrown into the fire and so 
the fire is white. 
the fire is cold, but the fish dip and move. 
the fire is not cold, but the fish dip and move. 
hard by a rock there is a place to sleep

======== SAMPLE 1 ========

       if thou findest the way, remember whereas 
       thine ear was of deep benefit tost, 
       and, remembering further, seek'st it more. 


       the clouds, like lambs that run before, 
       come up on holy mornings, 
       and give all their weight 
       to thy hearth-fire, head-fire and achilles, 
       which in their midst lie 
       in a thick cloud. 
       though heaven's command shakes them, 
       still thy hearth-fire shall uplift 
       thy saints by thy salvation. 

all-chosen, the song shall be, that shall say, 
in the land that just thou art, 
that lived the gospel of the good 
a year of gladness and of the good. 
all-chosen, the song shall be, because thou art 
thy deed was right and thy mouth art right, 
a just and a gracious way. 
all-chosen, the song, which shall give all thy goods, 
once more shall they that sung thy praise 
in the old years of our yoke 
to sing shall all the saints join 
as they, while they who sing now, hear.


in times of distress
no person of note
danceth, the multitudes
beneath the soundless sky
is new-born, the very few
that are about us. trouble 
hurleth away their counsels,
disturbs their affections
foes their hearts, their affection
hath them some work or remedy? 
thou knowest, and they that will
       do that which they cannot.

       counsels have to men such
       as are of service
       nevertheless
the evils for which 
       life writeth out 
       are of the soul. 
       therefore the way 
       is gloom to him 
       whose understanding 
       is still as in his day 
       and all the world conspires 
       in his doom.

       it is for his people, then, 
       from thee to inherit 
       everything, not of the door 
       only the deepest sense
is in his favour, and in his hand 
the terrible mystery gathers 
for him to enter and exercise. 
       counsels have to men such
       as are of service,
       to dwell in the day 
       and to hear the voice. 

       and if people, and counsels,
       the bard, to the work
       in wrath and gloom 
       of those whom judgement
       throws down, 
       like meteors 
       that run the long way, 
       or those lost in night, 
       for ever,
       and for the hour 
       has denuded and increas'd 
       of what might have been. 

       if people, and counsels,
       the king shall regard. 
       be merry, if they call
       a trifle what if to eat 
       for is good food. 
       if people, and counsels,
       the king shall regard, 
       that are wits,
       that do the work
       that are wits.

       if people, and counsels,
       have the will
       to help the king,

======== SAMPLE 1 ========
 in the midst of this endless
dream of what it's like to be somebody


this just-barely visible, bare
plane
we are far from home
and the bare plane shows
small intestines
 protruding, white,
stingy. there here's the one
we fly through
on our way to the airport.



winking at the great thrush's head-snapper's
ninja line
around, snarling
under the bar
cold in my bones

i'm wearing a nougaid hat
i can't bring
back to life.



it's not about snakes,
reptiles, gods among
human forms--it's
if you fell in with a snake
it would be red

not a white or red
fur, no eyes.

it's a field of numb
crawling skunks
under the apple
bush.



by now, you should see me
and know why i come to chicago
sometimes--not ny

but you should have seen me
on the interstate, hawking
quit repeat, a new scar tattoo
on my rear. the first time

i shaved my arm
with a butcher's wool knife
smoothed the skin til the skin
gleamed under my loose

eyes, the next year i'd
kissed it and called it love.
then, for awhile, i did

a walk through the field and
throated a door
to get me warm off
the blood of innocents.

now, i keep it on
out cold, thinking
of those snake
killers.



here is the river with a river inside,                                                                  as the crow flies.                                                                                                 --michael harper 


the beast won't let you sleep in april's leafless oak 
the river leafless beyond the river 
as the leafless oak flies into it 
the river we'll paddle out in full moon                                            and then we'll disappear                                            into the wake of night                                                    as the daniel o'hare 


he waltzed between bundles of solar cells, 
and wrapped his arms around their acrobatic 
horizontal necking. in mid-air, 

i'd like to imagine his glacial shoulder 
filled with dry earth, rolled up in towels, 
set on his back in the air like a globe. 

it would be funny, i suppose, to have a neighbor 
come inside who happens to be 

miserable to experience 
him as he spirals through space 
leaving one satellite 

with a last flare on the way, 
while the other coast 
repels the never-ending twinges 
of his disembodied gaze. 

then, of course, we have the relaxing 
dance of the just wrapped dancer-- 
wheel your bike around the bit and 

step as i do, head over heels through 
these landscapes, sighing 
through my legs and thighs 
as we twinkle past the vanishing point.

like a burrito made of air,   
like a hairdryer on hiatus,   
like a kitchen radio with a little   
on the stereo. change happens in the rear   
and
